			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-06-17T22:00:32+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">June 17, 2015 6:00 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">June 17, 2015 6:00 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/18/world/17sino-letter05/17sino-letter05-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/18/world/17sino-letter05/17sino-letter05-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/18/world/17sino-letter05/17sino-letter05-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003746383" width="592" height="395" alt="A woman walking along the Shanghai Bund against the Pudong district skyline."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A woman walking along the Shanghai Bund against the Pudong district skyline.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Aly Song/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/06/17/explaining-china-in-its-own-varied-terms/" data-title="Explaining China in Its Own (Varied) Terms" data-description="Zhang Weiwei, whose ââChina modelââ theory of development has influenced top leaders, employs more Confucius and statistics than Marx to explain why China under the Communist Party is certain to succeed.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Over dinner at the Fuxuan Hotel in Shanghai,  <a href="//sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/06/12/q-and-a-zhang-weiwei-on-why-china-will-succeed-under-the-communist-party/?module=BlogPost-Title&#038;version=Blog%20Main&#038;contentCollection=World&#038;action=Click&#038;pgtype=Blogs&#038;region=Body" title="Sinosphere post.">Zhang Weiwei</a>  explains why China under the Communist Party is certain to succeed, confounding the pessimistic predictions of Western naysayers.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Zhang, a 57-year-old politics professor at  <a href="//www.fudan.edu.cn/en/" title="University website (in English).">Fudan University</a> whose ââChina modelââ theory of authoritarian political and economic development has influenced top leaders, employs more Confucius and statistics than Marx to make his point. But this is China, where contradictions abound and everyone is comfortable with that.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We eat quickly, to make a lecture at the ââChina Narrative High-Level Forum,ââ a series Mr. Zhang has organized at the university. Shi Zhengfu, an economist, will take on the daunting task of constructing a coherent narrative of Chinaâs dizzying development since the Cultural Revolution ended in 1976. The lectures should help counter ââbad-mouthingââ of China by foreigners, Mr. Zhang says, by telling them Chinaâs own story. <span id="more-32764"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Over the simple meal in a private dining room of the hotel, Mr. Zhang talks about numbers. And Chinaâs own idea of good government.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Its size means a ââWesternââ approach to liberty that takes the rights of the individual as a starting point wonât work. ââChina is a supersize country. A supersize society. Supersize in that it has a lot of people. Its size is about 100 European countries,ââ he says. ââSo how to deal with Chinaâs problems?ââ</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">ââTake, for example, a primary school with 60 students, and a university like Fudan with 20,000 students. Itâs also a school. But they have to be managed completely differently. You want to deal with individual cases, but you focus on the scale. This enables society to develop better,ââ he continues. There arenât enough lawyers to go the legal route. ââWe want to use other ways to solve problems, for example administration intervention or politics.ââ</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Dinner over, we rush to the lecture, and I mention the Magna Carta, the ââcharter of libertyââ the English King John accepted under pressure from rebellious barons 800 years ago.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">ââChina has thought about that already. Itâs a basic consideration of our leaders,ââ Mr. Zhang said. ââConfucius said,  âWater can lift a boat, but it can also overturn it.â ââ In other words, self-preservation produces good government.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">ââI think the main problem, the main reason so many Westerners and Western media criticize us, is ideological. But Chinaâs is not a Soviet Union-style Communist Party. And weâre fed up,ââ he says, face crinkling in disgust.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At the lecture I sit next to a 20-year-old economics undergraduate named Charles Liu.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Liu says he is there because it is a rare opportunity to hear an analysis of Chinaâs economy by a Chinese economist.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">ââA lot of fellow students and I, we are proud of Chinaâs amazing successes in economic reform and curious about the reasons for it,ââ he  says. Mainstream economic theory comes mostly from Western economists, he adds, ââbut they donât really understand China.ââ</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Politically, he agrees with Mr. Zhang. American democracy has been hijacked by wealthy interest groups and is failing. China has great experience with running a country based on meritocracy, not democracy, and that is a great advantage, he says. But he too does not cite Marx as a guide, but rather Chinese tradition, looking to the Tang and Song dynasties.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Struck by party loyalists&#8217; regular recourse to Chinese tradition instead of Marx to explain good government, I shift the ground and ask Mr. Zhang, some days after the event, to talk about Marx. Can he comment on a tantalizing passage in the ââManifesto of the Communist Partyââ where Marx wrote, ââThe free development of each is the condition for the free development of allââ? </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The partyâs founding father seemed to be saying that individual liberty is essential. Do the authoritarians have a problem there? </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">To this too, Mr. Zhang has an answer. Marxâs call, he says, is understood in China as ââan ideal stage to be reached in a long distant future from now.ââ</p>
	</div>
